WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
My name is Matt Herman. I am a data scientist at the Council of State Governments Justice Center.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:17.000
We are a non-profit research and policy organization working on criminal justice issues.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:24.000
And I think for folks that are here today, not to see Jenny and Hadley's travel pictures, which were lovely,

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:31.000
but maybe you saw the subtitle of my talk and you're really interested in this cool, new, get-rich-quick, multi-level marketing scheme.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:37.000
So, I'm just going to jump straight to that part of the story here and introduce you first to Kyle Walker.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Kyle is a geography professor, and he's also the developer of a number of great R and Python packages, including the tidycensus package.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And in 2019, he sent me this direct message on Twitter. He says, hey, Matt, do you do any consulting?

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:59.000
I received a tidycensus consulting request, but I'm booked solid. Let me know if you're interested.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:08.000
So, I got this message. I got really, really excited, played it super cool, and waited three hours to respond.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.000
And I said, hey, Kyle, haven't done much consulting, but definitely interested.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
And Kyle said, sounds good. I'm passed along your email address.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:22.000
So, for I think a lot of people, getting a message like this or a conversation like this might be sort of normal,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
not that out of the ordinary. But for me, it was really surprising.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
I didn't feel like consulting material at that point.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
When I was an undergraduate, I never took any technical classes, no computer science.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.000
I mostly hung out at my college radio station.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
After college, I ended up working in public radio, and then I made my way into the food business.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:51.000
I helped my friend open a butcher shop that was called N's Meat. Get it?

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:56.000
And then eventually ended up in graduate school for sociology.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
But I did have one thing going for me here, and that's that I really knew the tidycensus package

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
and how to use it really, really well.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:09.000
For folks in the room who aren't familiar with tidycensus, it's a really cool R package

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:15.000
that lets you get data from the U.S. Census Bureau directly into your R session via web API.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And so, this makes it really easy to do all sorts of neat stuff,

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:24.000
like make a map of household income by census tract in Chicago.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And to make this map, you really just need a few lines of tidycensus and ggplot2 code.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:37.000
So, that first code chunk is pulling that data and also the geometries from the census API into your R session,

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:43.000
and then a couple lines of ggplot2 code to make this beautiful map.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:48.000
But my talk today really is not about how to use tidycensus, and it's not about Twitter.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:50.000
It's not about consulting.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:56.000
It's more about how I went from working in a butcher shop to getting consulting gigs

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
to being able to speak to you today at this conference.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And what I'm going to argue today in this conference is that really anyone who knows how to write code for data analysis

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:17.000
or data visualization in R can and probably already should, like can and should,

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:20.000
become a package developer, too, or at least a package contributor.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
And I think you already have the tools to do this.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
This is my daughter, Tessie.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:32.000
She's two, and she's really into water and really wanted to learn how to swim this summer.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:39.000
So, we're good parents, so we didn't just pick her up and drop her off into the deepest body of water we could find

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:41.000
and see if she floated.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:42.000
We didn't do that.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
We brought her to this beautiful lake where we live in Vermont and let her explore, you know,

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.000
walk into the water, get wet, splash around, see how it feels.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:57.000
And so, if you are ready for your R package development journey, I do not recommend going

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
and finding a very high diving board and jumping in the deep end.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Please don't start by submitting a package to CRAN.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:13.000
That's not going to be fun in the same way that I don't think we should drop Tessie into the deep end of a pool.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:18.000
So, one good way I think that you can start is with GitHub issues.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
I think most folks in the room are probably familiar with GitHub.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
It's a place where a lot of R packages are stored.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.000
Issues are a really, really wonderful place to ask a question about an R package,

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:33.000
or maybe you found a bug in a package you used, or maybe there's a feature you'd like to request,

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.000
and you can just post that up on GitHub, and it's a really good place to start.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:43.000
In fact, for me, that is my and was my first contribution to the tidy census package.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
I was in graduate school doing a lot of work and research using census data,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
and I discovered R, discovered tidy census.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:57.000
I liked using that much better than the census website, and I was hooked right away.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
So, this is actually my first contribution to tidy census.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.000
This is an issue I opened July 2017.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:09.000
And I say, I just started exploring tidy census today, and I love it.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
One question, is there a way to get one-year versus five-year estimates?

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Details here are not important.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
But then I go on to write, as much more of an R user than a programmer,

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.000
I can't help with actually implementing this feature, but I certainly would use this.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:23.000
A few weeks go by.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:28.000
The aforementioned Kyle Walker says, this functionality is now supported.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.000
So, this is amazing for a lot of reasons.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:38.000
First, we have a document of the day I started using tidy census, which is apparently July 17th, 2017.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.000
Great day.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
But also, so I had this idea.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:44.000
I knew about census data.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.000
I wanted to get a different kind of census data that wasn't currently available in tidy census.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And then all of a sudden, a few weeks later, the package developer, Kyle,

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:56.000
made some changes to the package, and now I could get this data.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
So, I was super stoked.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Also, any other user of tidy census also could sort of take advantage of this,

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
and now they can get this great data.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:12.000
So, for Kyle, as a package developer, he was getting direct user feedback.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:17.000
Maybe he hadn't thought that users might want to specify one-year versus five-year data.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:23.000
So, this got me really excited about R, about tidy census, and about GitHub and package development.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:29.000
And so, I continued on following the tidy census GitHub repository, paying attention to the issues,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
learning more about the package and how things worked.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And what I ended up doing is actually starting to respond to GitHub issues.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
So, this is from a few months later.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:47.000
GitHub user BigCK2, it's a very cool username, asked a question about getting five-year data from 2016.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
And I happened to know the answer to this question, and I write here,

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.000
oh, yeah, you can do this, but you've got to install the dev version from GitHub.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:59.000
BigCK2 says, great, I downloaded the dev version, and it works great.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.000
Thank you.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
So, this is really great for a lot of reasons, too.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
One, BigCK2 gets the answer to his question, now he can get the data.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
Second, if someone else has this exact same issue, hopefully they find this GitHub issue,

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:17.000
and they know, oh, I just have to install the dev version.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:24.000
And third, Kyle, the main package developer and maintainer, didn't have to do anything here.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
He can spend his time writing R code, not responding to GitHub issues.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:35.000
But I, as a TidySenses user enthusiast, could help out BigCK2.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:41.000
And I continued on this sort of path, learning more about the package, responding to more GitHub issues,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:44.000
and I sort of have direct evidence here of Kyle appreciating this.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:51.000
So, at some point in some other GitHub issue that we were talking about, Kyle says, MF Herman, that was me, you're the best.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.000
I'm putting you down as a package contributor on the next CRAN release for answering so many user questions.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.000
So, this was really exciting to me.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:03.000
Again, didn't see myself, still don't really see myself as a programmer or coder,

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:12.000
but now I'm a co-author or contributor to this awesome package that I love to use.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
So, let's say you're ready to get a little bit deeper into the water.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
You're starting with the doggy paddle, you're maybe going up to your neck a little bit,

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
and you want to actually start contributing some code to a package.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:29.000
I think bug fixes, simple bug fixes, are a really great place to start.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:34.000
Along this journey, maybe you also are reading the R packages book.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
You're understanding a little bit more about DevTools,

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:42.000
and you kind of want to apply some of these things you're learning about into a package that you like to use.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And this is exactly what I did.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:50.000
So, this is, I don't know, looks like December 2018.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:58.000
I noticed a bug that was related to an update to TIBL that was causing some downstream issues in TidyCensus.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Not a really big deal, but it was a bug and it needed to be taken care of.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
And so, I hunted around in the code.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:12.000
I remember it really took a really long time to figure out where this bug was occurring.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:13.000
I didn't really know.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.000
I didn't have that whole workflow, the beautiful load all, check, test, all that stuff.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:18.000
I didn't really understand.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:19.000
It was a lot of manual hunting.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:22.000
But I tracked down this bug, and I thought that was really cool.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
I figured out how to make it work on my computer.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
And then I made this pull request on GitHub.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:34.000
Also note, this pull request is tiny, like 11 lines of code, really, really small.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
But, again, this is another example.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
This was an issue that genuinely had to be fixed when TIBL was going to be updated.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:47.000
And this is something that, again, Kyle, with limited amount of time to devote to resources, didn't have to do.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:49.000
He looked at my code.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:50.000
It worked.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
And he was able to merge.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
So, this is a really great way to contribute and to get your feet wet a little bit more.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
Again, 11 lines of code.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:03.000
I think a next step that might be if you want to sort of keep going on this path, and this is what I did here,

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
is think about a small feature that you might want to add to the package.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:07.000
Nothing big.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:11.000
Not whole new functions or anything like that.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:14.000
For me, there was a sort of convenience function,

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:19.000
an additional argument that I wanted to add to one of the core TidyCensus packages.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:23.000
Core TidyCensus functions that I thought would make a user's life a little bit easier.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And I had this idea.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:25.000
I figured out how to code it up.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
Seemed like it was working.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And, again, pull request.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
It got merged.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:38.000
Again, 101 lines of code added not a really big sort of addition to the package in the grand scheme of things.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
But this was, for me, a really exciting moment.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:46.000
Because what this meant was there was a new argument in the getACS function.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.000
And so, not only could I use that because it was useful for me,

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:55.000
but anyone else who installed this package from GitHub or CRAN now had access to that function.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:02.000
And so that meant, like, my code lived on tens or hundreds or thousands of people's computers.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:06.000
And, again, that to me was a really good feeling.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:15.000
And it made me feel more like this package developer, not just that R user that I started as.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:23.000
A third way that I think you can really make a lot of impact on your package contributions is by taking your domain knowledge.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
The thing that you know better than anyone else.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
And figure out a way to encode that into an R package.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:34.000
Encode that into, somehow, R functions or documentation.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:37.000
I've always really loved this quote from Zed Shaw.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:41.000
He says, programming as a profession is only moderately interesting.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:46.000
You're much better off using code as your secret weapon in another profession.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
And this is exactly how I felt.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:54.000
You know, I was coming at this studying sociology and other sorts of social research.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:59.000
I was never going to be a professional programmer, but I did know a lot about census data.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
I did know a lot about other kinds of social research.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:06.000
And so the idea here is that that was my secret weapon, right?

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:14.000
I couldn't write the most amazing R code in the world, but was there some way that I could take what I knew about the census

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:20.000
and what I knew about sociology and put that into the R package somehow.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.000
And so this is exactly what Kyle and I worked on next.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
And this was actually a big new feature.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
It allowed users to get census micro data.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:34.000
So instead of summarized data where you just say a count of how many people live in a certain area,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:40.000
you could actually get individual lines of data that represented responses to the American Community Survey directly into your R session.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
So this is really neat.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And along with this, I worked on a package vignette.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:51.000
Vignette is essentially documentation, an article about how to use your package.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:58.000
So this is the vignette called working with census micro data that you can find on the Tidy Census website right now.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:02.000
And I do want to just point out the table of contents here.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:10.000
So if you look at some of these things, I'm talking about PUMAs, public use micro data area, person level data, housing level data,

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
how to calculate standard errors.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
None of this is about R code.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
None of this is about R programming.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:23.000
This is about the stuff that I know about, census data, and it's in an R package.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:30.000
So this is, again, providing huge value in getting all that domain knowledge out of my head and into an R package through documentation

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:35.000
so that users who might be interested in this also can benefit from it.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:38.000
Around this time, Kyle sent me another Twitter DM.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.000
He says, changed your role on package to co-author.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:45.000
And this didn't really mean much to anybody, but now my name is on the Tidy Census website.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:54.000
And, again, this is another sort of point of validation for me, and it felt really good to be a co-author of this package.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:00.000
So what I hope to sort of get across here is that there's lots of different ways to contribute to packages.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:06.000
And I think this map of sort of how I did it, starting with GitHub issues, just asking them,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:14.000
then maybe responding to GitHub issues that you see, maybe level up and get into fixing little bugs or adding small new features,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:21.000
and then eventually taking what you know outside of R package development and try to insert it into the package framework

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:28.000
is, like, really powerful, and there's a lot of good reasons for why I think everyone who's an R user might want to do this.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And I think of them along sort of two dimensions here.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
The first is becoming a tool builder.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.000
So you're going to improve your R programming skills markedly.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:43.000
When you start thinking about writing functions, you're learning about abstracting your code and writing modular and generalizable code.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
You're going to learn all about unit tests and how important those are.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
You're also going to learn a lot about Git and GitHub.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:53.000
Maybe if you're a solo R user, you might use Git just for version control on your own.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:57.000
But once you're in the package development world, you're all about collaboration.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:04.000
And so you're going to learn really quickly about forks and clones and merge requests and merge conflicts and all that fun GitHub stuff.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And I think ultimately what this does is make you more desirable to an employer because you can say, not only do I know how to use R,

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
I'm also an R package developer.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:18.000
Also, I know how to use Git and GitHub really well.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:23.000
The other domain that I kind of think of this on is on community contributions.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:29.000
So you, through this, are going to be able to meet other R users online.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
I've never actually met Kyle in person.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
But as you can see, we've communicated a lot on Twitter, on GitHub, and other places.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:38.000
And I kind of think of him as a friend.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
You're also going to be able to grow and sustain the open source community.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:51.000
So as R users, we all have benefited so much from so many people who have volunteered their time to contribute to the open source community.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:58.000
And so me, now, as a Tidy Census co-author, I'm able to give back in just a little bit, a little way,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
and show my appreciation for that community and help grow it and help sustain it.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:09.000
And then you might get really cool opportunities like being able to stand up on the stage and speak to you at PositConf.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:14.000
And sort of interestingly enough here, there is some documentation of this.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
I wrote this Twitter message to Kyle.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.000
I said, hey, I've been toying with the idea of submitting a talk proposal.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
I doubt it will get accepted, but just wanted to make sure it was cool with you.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.000
And Kyle says, yeah, of course, go for it.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:33.000
I do want to note here, I sent this to him in August of 2020, and I was talking about RStudioConf 2021.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:34.000
Life got in the way.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:35.000
There was a global pandemic.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
My daughter Tessie was born.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
Didn't end up submitting it then.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:53.000
But what I really think that I learned from this whole journey is that it's never too early in your R programming career to start contributing to R packages.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.000
And there's lots of different ways to do it.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:01.000
Also, apparently it's never too late to apply to speak at PositConf.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:11.000
Thank you.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
Thanks, Matt. That was great.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.000
We do have a little bit of time for questions if you want to ask one or two.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
Anyone from the audience?

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:24.000
There's none on Slido right now, but if you do have a question, I can come to you with the microphone.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:28.000
